Two CNOT gates used by the QCC ansatz should be contrasted with 64 two-qubit C X gates that are needed to implement the UCC form in CAS(2,2). [A circuit diagram from which the gate counts are read was generated with the ProjectQ framework. (36,37) ] These numbers clearly show that the QCC method is far superior in the number of two-qubit gates.
Entanglers for LiH
Due to a larger number of entangled spin–orbitals in LiH, the list of entanglers is more complex. Near the equilibrium bond length, R (Li–H) ≈ 1.5 Å, our procedure readily identifies a few (six to seven) entanglers that give chemical accuracy. However, these entanglers do not provide chemical accuracy for the whole curve, R (Li–H) from 0.5 to 5.0 Å. The region where QMF experiences symmetry breaking, R (Li–H) ≳ 3.2 Å, is especially demanding: the list of energetically important entanglers grows substantially, and calculating the same entanglers’ characteristics as before does not shrink it considerably. To achieve reduction, we noticed that since the QMF reference has broken symmetry while the exact eigenstate has the singlet symmetry, it is prudent to search for entanglers that can not only lower the energy but also restore the spin symmetry. To assess the capability of entanglers for symmetry restoration, we calculate the gradient of individual energies on a spin-singlet constraint QMF solution, | Ω c,min ⟩: (33) These gradients are larger for those entanglers that can affect the symmetry of the constrained QMF solution. Using seven of such entanglers, which also have high individual energy lowerings ( Table 2 ), we were able to reach the chemical accuracy for the whole LiH potential energy curve ( Figure 3 ) . Interestingly, these entanglers that can not only restore symmetry but also break it work well for nuclear geometries where symmetry restoration is not needed. We attribute this to the ability of the variational procedure to find amplitudes for the symmetry affecting entanglers so that they do not break QMF symmetry where it is unnecessary.
