Δ E [ P ] are evaluated with respect to the symmetry constrained QMF energies.
Applying our factorization procedure to split three- and four-qubit entanglers in Table 2 gives 31 two-qubit entanglers, but some of them may be canceled in the final product. As a result, only 38 two-qubit gates are necessary for implementing the QCC ansatz on a quantum computer. The factorization does not change the number of variational parameters and their total number in the QCC procedure was 2 × 4 + 7 = 15.
If we compare our QCC ansatz with alternatives from the literature for LiH, we find the following. The QPE method with the first-order Trotterization will use ∼100 (the number of terms in the qubit Hamiltonian) exponential factors. Each factor gives rise to two or more two-qubit entanglement gates in the circuit decomposition and hence, several hundreds of two-qubit gates are needed.
Comparison with UCC is more involved. Since UCC works with Fermionic operators, one cannot exploit qubit symmetries. Thus, Fermionic excitations are generated for the original CAS(2e,3o). Limiting consideration by single and double excitations (UCCSD), we found 272 two-qubit gates in the quantum circuit. More fair comparison would be if a procedure to exploit qubit symmetries could be implemented for UCC, but we are not aware of such implementation.
Finally, the form of Kandala et al. (21) seems to be the most economical one: chemical accuracy was achieved with d = 6, which implies at least six pairwise entanglers. However, Kandala et al. (21) use significantly more variational parameters: for four qubits and d = 6 the count is 80. The excessive parametrization makes energy minimization considerably more difficult since the expectation values provided by a quantum computer have inherent quantum uncertainty.
Entanglers for H 2 O
We systematically screened all 4077 two- to six-qubit entanglers at R (O–H) = 1.25 Å; see the Supporting Information for details. Even the first-order selection protocol, eq 25 , identified significantly more entanglers than can be included in QCC simulations in the current implementation. To assess the capabilities of the QCC method notwithstanding, we manually selected one four-qubit entangler that had (among others) the largest value of gradient, T̂ 0 = x̂ 4 x̂ 3 x̂ 1 ŷ 0 , added another four top-ranked linearly independent entanglers T̂ 1–4 = ẑ 2 T̂ 0 , ẑ 5 T̂ 0 , ẑ 2 ẑ 5 T̂ 0 , and x̂ 2 x̂ 5 T̂ 0 , which couple qubits (4, 3, 1, 0) with the remaining qubits, and added three mutually commuting two-qubit entanglers with largest gradients that provide pairwise relaxation of qubit degrees of freedom within and outside the cluster: T̂ 5 = x̂ 0 ŷ 2 , T̂ 6 = ŷ 1 x̂ 4 , and T̂ 7 = x̂ 3 ŷ 5 .
These eight entanglers provide chemical accuracy only near the equilibrium geometry. Contrary to the traditional CCSD counterpart, the QCC potential energy curve stays above the exact one (see Figure 4 ), which is a result of the variational nature of QCC. Our QCC ansatz represented as a quantum circuit (35) uses 48 two-qubit CNOT gates. Similar to the case of LiH we could not exploit qubit symmetries and generated UCCSD Fermionic excitations for the original CAS(4,4) . The corresponding quantum circuit contains 1312 two-qubit C X gates. [Gate decomposition is done with ProjectQ .]
Figure 4

Figure 4. Potential energy curves for the symmetric stretch of the water molecule.
High Resolution Image
Download MS PowerPoint Slide
To address the problem of exponential growth of entanglers for screening in QCC, one can use qubit images of rank-limited UCC cluster operators. This will generate a shorter list of Pauli words than in the full lexicographical ordered list of entanglers. Such a hybrid approach combines Fock-space and Hilbert-space screening procedures and allows for even more resource-efficient schemes.
4. Conclusions
ARTICLE SECTIONS
Jump To

    Abstract
    Introduction
    Theory
    Numerical Studies and Discussion
    Conclusions
    Appendix: Qubit Coupled Cluster Energy Derivatives
    Supporting Information
    Acknowledgments
    References

We have introduced and studied a new method for performing electronic structure calculations on a quantum computer. We called our method the qubit coupled cluster (QCC) to emphasize that it is rooted in the unitary coupled cluster (UCC) theory but, contrary to UCC, formulated without any reference to Fermionic algebra exclusively in terms of qubit operators.
From the mathematical point of view, QCC is a variational method where variational optimization of single-qubit rotations and multiqubit unitary transformation are done altogether. The single-qubit Hilbert space is parametrized in terms of spin coherent states which depend on Bloch angles. There are only two angles per qubit, and terms of the qubit Hamiltonian have exceptionally simple expressions for matrix elements in the chosen basis.
The essential feature of the QCC form is the multiqubit unitary transformations in terms of Pauli words—products of Pauli operators. Such transformations are the simplest possible in the qubit tensor algebra; they lead to a compact economical form of unitarily transformed operators such as the Hamiltonian itself ( eq 20 ). This simplicity allows for extremely frugal use of quantum resources such as two-qubit entanglement gates. Moreover, we derived the decomposition of a multiqubit unitary rotation to a product of two-qubit unitary rotations, eq 32 . This formula can make simulations of highly entangled systems possible on hardware that is limited by entanglement of only two qubits.
Formulations of the quantum chemistry in the qubit space have several complications. First, even though only isospectral Fermionic-to-qubit transformations are employed, and thus all symmetries of the Fermionic system are replicated in its qubit counterpart, this is not generally true for approximate methods. Indeed, in ref (28) , we found that breaking of physical symmetries, such as the number of electrons or spin, in qubit variational methods is more a rule than an exception. At the same time, this problem can be solved by using appropriate constraints. Second, by treating a molecular system directly in the qubit space, it is not straightforward to use typical electronic structure intuition, for example, information about whether this system is weakly correlated like a closed-shell molecule near equilibrium geometry, or strongly correlated like an open-shell radical with many quasi-degenerate orbitals. We address this shortcoming by devising the derivative test, eq 25 , which allows one to tailor the QCC ansatz to a given molecular system in an efficient manner.
We illustrate our approach by considering the dissociation of the H 2 and LiH molecules in the minimal basis and symmetric water dissociation in the Pople 6-31G basis set. (32) These systems represent increasingly more complex examples of quantum entanglement. In all cases we identified a short list (one to eight entries) of entanglers mainly due to implementation limitations. However, even such short expansions were shown to be efficient. For H 2 the exact solution requires only one entangler, for LiH chemical accuracy (≤1 kcal/mol) for the whole potential curve is achieved, and for H 2 O we calculated a physically correct potential energy curve with chemical accuracy near the potential minimum. We hope, therefore, that the QCC method will become the method of choice for quantum chemistry on a quantum computer in near future.
